    "cooking_instructions": [
        {
            "instruction": "<p><strong>Seal the duck legs</strong></p> <p>Preheat the oven to 160&ordm;C/ 140&ordm;C (fan)/ 350&ordm;F/ Gas 4.</p> <p>Heat a large, wide-based pan (preferably non-stick) with a drizzle of <strong>vegetable oil</strong> over a high heat.</p> <p>Once very hot, add the<strong> duck legs</strong> with a generous pinch of&nbsp;<strong>salt</strong>&nbsp;and cook for 4-5 minutes or until browned all over.</p> <p>Once browned, transfer the <strong>duck</strong> to a plate and reserve the pan.</p>",
            "order": 1,
            "image": "/images/instructions/red-wine-braised-duck-leg-mustard-mash-heritage-carrots-and-beans/step-1.jpg"
        },
        {
            "instruction": "<p><strong>Prepare the onion and shallots</strong></p> <p>Meanwhile, peel and finely dice the&nbsp;<strong>onion<span class=\"text-danger\">[s]</span></strong>.</p> <p>Peel and halve the&nbsp;<strong>shallots</strong>.</p> <p>Boil a kettle.</p>",
            "order": 2,
            "image": "/images/instructions/red-wine-braised-duck-leg-mustard-mash-heritage-carrots-and-beans/step-2.jpg"
        },
        {
            "instruction": "<p><strong>Caramelise the mushrooms</strong></p> <p>Discard some of the <strong>fat</strong> from the pan so you're left with just 1 tbsp <span class=\"text-danger\">[2 tbsp]</span>. Return it to a medium heat.</p> <p>Once hot, add the&nbsp;<strong>diced onion</strong>&nbsp;and<strong>&nbsp;chestnut mushrooms&nbsp;</strong>and cook for 5-6 minutes or until beginning to soften and caramelise.</p> <p>Meanwhile, dissolve the&nbsp;<strong>chicken stock cube<span class=\"text-danger\">[s]</span></strong>&nbsp;and the&nbsp;<strong>Just Add Wine sachet<span class=\"text-danger\">[s]</span></strong>&nbsp;in 400ml&nbsp;<span class=\"text-danger\">[700ml]</span>&nbsp;<strong>boiled water</strong>.</p>",
            "order": 3,
            "image": "/images/instructions/red-wine-braised-duck-leg-mustard-mash-heritage-carrots-and-beans/step-3.jpg"
        },
        {
            "instruction": "<p><strong>Prepare your stew for the oven</strong></p> <p>Once caramelised, add 1 tbsp&nbsp;<span class=\"text-danger\">[2 tbsp]</span>&nbsp;<strong>flour</strong>&nbsp;to the&nbsp;<strong>onion&nbsp;</strong>and<strong>&nbsp;mushrooms</strong>,&nbsp;give everything a good mix up and cook for 1-2 minutes.</p> <p>Gradually add the <strong>wine stock</strong> to the pan and cook for 1 minute or until combined.</p> <p>Add the<strong> duck legs</strong> to an <strong>oven-proof dish</strong> with the <strong>shallots</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>bay leaves</strong>.</p> <p>Pour the&nbsp;wine braise&nbsp;all over and cover the dish tightly with <strong>tin foil</strong> (or a matching lid).</p> <p>&nbsp;</p>",
            "order": 4,
            "image": "/images/instructions/red-wine-braised-duck-leg-mustard-mash-heritage-carrots-and-beans/step-4.jpg"
        },
        {
            "instruction": "<p><strong>Braise the duck</strong></p> <p>Put the dish in the oven for 1 hour 30 minutes or until the duck is tender. Re-boil a kettle.</p> <p>Once the duck has had 1 hour and 15 minutes, peel and chop the&nbsp;<strong>potatoes</strong>&nbsp;into rough, bite-sized pieces.</p> <p>Add the&nbsp;<strong>chopped potatoes&nbsp;</strong>to a pot of&nbsp;<strong>boiling water</strong>&nbsp;with a pinch of&nbsp;<strong>salt</strong>&nbsp;over a high heat and cook for 10-15 minutes or until fork-tender.</p> <p>Once cooked, drain and return them to the pot.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p>",
            "order": 5,
            "image": "/images/instructions/red-wine-braised-duck-leg-mustard-mash-heritage-carrots-and-beans/step-5.jpg"
        },
        {
            "instruction": "<p><strong>Crispen the duck </strong></p> <p>Once the duck has had 1 hour and 30 minutes, increase the oven to 220&deg;C/ 200&deg;C (fan)/ 425&deg;F/ Gas 7.</p> <p>Remove the foil from the dish and cook for 20 minutes further or until the <strong>duck</strong> is crispy and the sauce has reduced to a gravy-like consistency.</p> <p>Meanwhile, clean and scrub the<strong>&nbsp;heritage baby carrots</strong> to remove any dirt (no need to peel!).</p> <p>Chop the <strong>chives </strong>and<strong>&nbsp;parsley</strong> finely.&nbsp;</p>",
            "order": 6,
            "image": "/images/instructions/red-wine-braised-duck-leg-mustard-mash-heritage-carrots-and-beans/step-6.jpg"
        },
        {
            "instruction": "<p><strong>Cook the heritage carrots and beans</strong></p> <p>Return the pan to a medium heat with a knob of<strong> butter</strong>.</p> <p>Once hot, add the <strong>carrots</strong> and cook for 3-4 minutes.</p> <p>Add the<strong> green beans</strong>&nbsp;with a&nbsp;pinch of <strong>salt</strong>&nbsp;and a splash of <strong>water</strong> and cook, covered, for 3-4 minutes or until tender.</p> <p>Return the<strong>&nbsp;potatoes</strong>&nbsp;to a low heat with a splash of&nbsp;<strong>milk</strong>&nbsp;and a knob of&nbsp;<strong>butter</strong>.</p> <p>Mash until smooth, then stir in the&nbsp;<strong>wholegrain mustard</strong>&nbsp;and season generously with&nbsp;<strong>salt</strong>.</p>",
            "order": 7,
            "image": "/images/instructions/red-wine-braised-duck-leg-mustard-mash-heritage-carrots-and-beans/step-7.jpg"
        },
        {
            "instruction": "<p><strong>Serve up! </strong></p> <p>Once the&nbsp;veg are cooked, sprinkle over the<strong>&nbsp;chopped parsley </strong>and<strong> chives</strong>&nbsp;and give everything a good mix up.&nbsp;</p> <p>Serve the <strong>red wine-braised duck leg</strong> over the<strong> mustard mash</strong> with the<strong> herby carrots</strong> and <strong>beans</strong> to the side.</p> <p>Enjoy!</p>",
            "order": 8
        }
    ],
